<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06098020 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06098020 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd said Saturday that talks with China onplans to build a new Hong Kong airport have apparently failed. Hurd soughtChina's support for a proposed $16.2 billion airport in the prosperous Britishcolony, which reverts to Chinese control in 1997. He said he offered theChinese a greater decision-making role in Hong Kong before 1997 as aconcession to win support for the project. The airport and related issuesdominated the three days of talks with Premier Li Peng and other officials,Hurd said. Beijing wants a new airport but says the current plans are tooexpensive and extravagant.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HONG KONG AIRPORT TOO COSTLY, CHINA SAYS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Foreign News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910407  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  17A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  109  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday April 7, 199100098020,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>